WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.630 --> 00:00:04.729
Professor Ben Polak:
Okay, so last time we came

00:00:04.729 --> 00:00:07.595
across a new idea,
although it wasn't very new for

00:00:07.595 --> 00:00:13.879
a lot of you,
and that was the idea of Nash

00:00:13.879 --> 00:00:17.604
Equilibrium.
What I want to do today is

00:00:17.604 --> 00:00:19.949
discuss Nash Equilibrium,
see how we find that

00:00:19.949 --> 00:00:22.190
equilibrium into rather simple
examples.

00:00:22.190 --> 00:00:24.804
And then in the second half of
the day I want to look at an

00:00:24.804 --> 00:00:27.600
application where we actually
have some fun and play a game.

00:00:27.600 --> 00:00:31.791
At least I hope it's fun.
But let's start by putting down

00:00:31.791 --> 00:00:35.343
a formal definition.
We only used a rather informal

00:00:35.343 --> 00:00:38.260
one last week,
so here's a formal one.

00:00:38.260 --> 00:00:44.448
A strategy profile--remember a
profile is one strategy for each

00:00:44.448 --> 00:00:48.940
player, so it's going to be
S_1*,

00:00:48.940 --> 00:00:51.853
S_2*,
all the way up to

00:00:51.853 --> 00:00:57.042
S_M* if there are M
players playing the game--so

00:00:57.042 --> 00:01:01.868
this profile is a Nash
Equilibrium (and I'm just going

00:01:01.868 --> 00:01:07.148
to write NE in this class for
Nash Equilibrium from now on)

00:01:07.148 --> 00:01:11.727
if,
for each i â€“so for each

00:01:11.727 --> 00:01:19.129
player i, her choice--so her
choice here is S_i*,

00:01:19.129 --> 00:01:34.130
i is part of that profile is a
best response to the other

00:01:34.130 --> 00:01:41.663
players' choices.
Of course, the other players'

00:01:41.663 --> 00:01:45.623
choices here are
S_--i* so everyone is

00:01:45.623 --> 00:01:49.330
playing a best response to
everyone else.

00:01:49.330 --> 00:01:54.186
Now, this is by far the most
commonly used solution concept

00:01:54.186 --> 00:01:56.740
in Game Theory.
So those of you who are

00:01:56.740 --> 00:01:59.639
interviewing for McKenzie or
something, you're going to find

00:01:59.639 --> 00:02:02.439
that they're going to expect you
to know what this is.

00:02:02.439 --> 00:02:04.635
So one reason for knowing what
it is, is because it's in the

00:02:04.635 --> 00:02:06.829
textbooks, it's going to be used
in lots of applications,

00:02:06.829 --> 00:02:08.520
it's going to be used in your
McKenzie interview.

00:02:08.520 --> 00:02:11.501
That's not a very good reason
and I certainly don't want you

00:02:11.501 --> 00:02:14.078
to jump to the conclusion that
now we've got to Nash

00:02:14.078 --> 00:02:17.110
Equilibrium everything we've
done up to know is in some sense

00:02:17.110 --> 00:02:19.009
irrelevant.
That's not the case.

00:02:19.009 --> 00:02:22.304
It's not always going to be the
case that people always play a

00:02:22.304 --> 00:02:23.907
Nash Equilibrium.
For example,

00:02:23.907 --> 00:02:26.648
when we played the numbers
game, the game when you chose a

00:02:26.648 --> 00:02:28.477
number,
we've already discussed last

00:02:28.477 --> 00:02:30.691
week or last time,
that the equilibrium in that

00:02:30.691 --> 00:02:32.520
game is for everyone to choose
one,

00:02:32.520 --> 00:02:35.437
but when we actually played the
game, the average was much

00:02:35.437 --> 00:02:37.740
higher than that:
the average was about 13.

00:02:37.740 --> 00:02:39.646
It is true that when we played
it repeatedly,

00:02:39.646 --> 00:02:41.120
it seemed to converge towards
1,

00:02:41.120 --> 00:02:44.279
but the play of the game when
we played it just one shot first

00:02:44.279 --> 00:02:47.222
time, wasn't a Nash Equilibrium.
So we shouldn't form the

00:02:47.222 --> 00:02:50.030
mistake of thinking people
always play Nash Equilibrium or

00:02:50.030 --> 00:02:52.789
people, "if they're rational,"
play Nash Equilibrium.

00:02:52.789 --> 00:02:54.819
Neither of those statements are
true.

00:02:54.819 --> 00:02:56.792
Nevertheless,
there are some good reasons for

00:02:56.792 --> 00:02:59.617
thinking about Nash Equilibrium
other than the fact it's used by

00:02:59.617 --> 00:03:02.594
other people,
and let's talk about those a

00:03:02.594 --> 00:03:05.480
bit.
So I want to put down some

00:03:05.480 --> 00:03:11.034
motivations here--the first
motivation we already discussed

00:03:11.034 --> 00:03:15.004
last time.
In fact, somebody in the

00:03:15.004 --> 00:03:20.227
audience mentioned it,
and it's the idea of "no

00:03:20.227 --> 00:03:22.800
regrets."
So what is this idea?

00:03:22.800 --> 00:03:26.720
It says, suppose we're looking
at a Nash Equilibrium.

00:03:26.720 --> 00:03:31.715
If we hold the strategies of
everyone else fixed,

00:03:31.715 --> 00:03:36.190
no individual i has an
incentive to deviate,

00:03:36.190 --> 00:03:38.660
to move away.
Alright, I'll say it again.

00:03:38.660 --> 00:03:42.544
Holding everyone else's actions
fixed, no individual has any

00:03:42.544 --> 00:03:45.832
incentive to move away.
Let me be a little more careful

00:03:45.832 --> 00:03:47.456
here;
no individual has any

00:03:47.456 --> 00:03:49.819
strict incentive to move
away.

00:03:49.819 --> 00:03:51.370
We'll see if that actually
matters.

00:03:51.370 --> 00:03:58.050
So no individual can do
strictly better by moving away.

00:03:58.050 --> 00:04:13.859
No individual can do strictly
better by deviating,

00:04:13.859 --> 00:04:24.830
holding everyone else's
actions.

00:04:24.830 --> 00:04:27.433
So why I call that "no regret"?
It means, having played the

00:04:27.433 --> 00:04:29.949
game, suppose you did in fact
play a Nash Equilibrium and then

00:04:29.949 --> 00:04:31.600
you looked back at what you had
done,

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:34.258
and now you know what everyone
else has done and you say,

00:04:34.258 --> 00:04:36.378
"Do I regret my actions?"
And the answer is,

00:04:36.378 --> 00:04:39.172
"No, I don't regret my actions
because I did the best I could

00:04:39.172 --> 00:04:41.760
given what they did."
So that seems like a fairly

00:04:41.760 --> 00:04:44.920
important sort of central idea
for why we should care about

00:04:44.920 --> 00:04:47.246
Nash Equilibrium.
Here's a second idea,

00:04:47.246 --> 00:04:50.250
and we'll see others arise in
the course of today.

00:04:50.250 --> 00:04:59.738
A second idea is that a Nash
Equilibrium can be thought of as

00:04:59.738 --> 00:05:05.134
self-fulfilling beliefs.
So, in the last week or so

00:05:05.134 --> 00:05:07.209
we've talked a fair amount about
beliefs.

00:05:07.209 --> 00:05:10.606
If I believe the goal keeper's
going to dive this way I should

00:05:10.606 --> 00:05:13.555
shoot that way and so on.
But of course we didn't talk

00:05:13.555 --> 00:05:16.113
about any beliefs in particular.
These beliefs,

00:05:16.113 --> 00:05:19.464
if I believe that--if everyone
in the game believes that

00:05:19.464 --> 00:05:23.181
everyone else is going to play
their part of a particular Nash

00:05:23.181 --> 00:05:26.221
Equilibrium then everyone,
will in fact,

00:05:26.221 --> 00:05:29.940
play their part of that Nash
Equilibrium.

00:05:29.940 --> 00:05:33.709
Now, why?
Why is it the case if everyone

00:05:33.709 --> 00:05:36.638
believes that everyone else is
playing their part of this

00:05:36.638 --> 00:05:39.933
particular Nash Equilibrium that
that's so fulfilling and people

00:05:39.933 --> 00:05:43.980
actually will play that way?
Why is that the case?

00:05:43.980 --> 00:05:48.399
Anybody?
Can we get this guy in red?

00:05:48.399 --> 00:05:50.995
Student: Because your
Nash Equilibrium matches the

00:05:50.995 --> 00:05:53.437
best response against both.
Professor Ben Polak:

00:05:53.437 --> 00:05:55.754
Exactly, so it's really--it's
almost a repeat of the first

00:05:55.754 --> 00:05:57.534
thing.
If I think everyone else is

00:05:57.534 --> 00:06:00.205
going to play their
particular--if I think players 2

00:06:00.205 --> 00:06:02.771
through N are going to play
S_2* through

00:06:02.771 --> 00:06:05.547
S_N*--then by
definition my best response is

00:06:05.547 --> 00:06:08.900
to play S_1* so I will
in fact play my part in the Nash

00:06:08.900 --> 00:06:11.397
Equilibrium.
Good, so as part of the

00:06:11.397 --> 00:06:14.920
definition, we can see these are
self-fulfilling beliefs.

00:06:14.920 --> 00:06:18.983
Let's just remind ourselves how
that arose in the example we

00:06:18.983 --> 00:06:22.319
looked at the end last time.
I'm not going to go back and

00:06:22.319 --> 00:06:24.360
re-analyze it,
but I just want to sort of make

00:06:24.360 --> 00:06:28.405
sure that we followed it.
So, we had this picture last

00:06:28.405 --> 00:06:34.055
time in the partnership game in
which people were choosing

00:06:34.055 --> 00:06:37.724
effort levels.
And this line was the best

00:06:37.724 --> 00:06:42.149
response for Player 1 as a
function of Player 2's choice.

00:06:42.149 --> 00:06:46.445
And this line was the best
response of Player 2 as a

00:06:46.445 --> 00:06:50.363
function of Player 1's choice.
This is the picture we saw last

00:06:50.363 --> 00:06:51.884
time.
And let's just look at how

00:06:51.884 --> 00:06:54.602
those--it's no secret here what
the Nash Equilibrium is:

00:06:54.602 --> 00:06:57.567
the Nash Equilibrium is where
the lines cross--but let's just

00:06:57.567 --> 00:07:00.680
see how it maps out to those two
motivations we just said.

00:07:00.680 --> 00:07:02.660
So, how about self-fulfilling
beliefs?

00:07:02.660 --> 00:07:06.671
Well, if Player--sorry,
I put 1, that should be 2--if

00:07:06.671 --> 00:07:10.837
Player 1 believes that Player 2
is going to choose this

00:07:10.837 --> 00:07:13.730
strategy,
then Player 1 should choose

00:07:13.730 --> 00:07:16.082
this strategy.
If Player 1 thinks Player 2

00:07:16.082 --> 00:07:18.639
should take this strategy,
then Player 1 should choose

00:07:18.639 --> 00:07:20.603
this strategy.
If Player 1 thinks Player 2 is

00:07:20.603 --> 00:07:22.510
choosing this strategy,
then Player I should choose

00:07:22.510 --> 00:07:24.772
this strategy and so on;
that's what it means to be best

00:07:24.772 --> 00:07:28.162
response.
But if Player 1 thinks that

00:07:28.162 --> 00:07:34.811
Player 2 is playing exactly her
Nash strategy then Player 1's

00:07:34.811 --> 00:07:41.459
best response is to respond by
playing his Nash strategy.

00:07:41.459 --> 00:07:45.297
And conversely,
if Player 2 thinks Player 1 is

00:07:45.297 --> 00:07:49.988
playing his Nash strategy,
then Player 2's best response

00:07:49.988 --> 00:07:53.399
indeed is to play her Nash
strategy.

00:07:53.399 --> 00:07:55.050
So, you can that's a
self-fulfilling belief.

00:07:55.050 --> 00:07:57.961
If both people think that's
what's going to happen,

00:07:57.961 --> 00:08:00.290
that is indeed what's going to
happen.

00:08:00.290 --> 00:08:02.200
How about the idea of no
regrets?

00:08:02.200 --> 00:08:03.731
So here's Player 1;
she wakes up the next

00:08:03.731 --> 00:08:05.170
morning--oh I'm sorry it was a
he wasn't it?

00:08:05.170 --> 00:08:07.954
He wakes up the next morning
and he says, "I chose

00:08:07.954 --> 00:08:10.000
S_1*,
do I regret this?"

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:12.110
Well, now he knows what Player
2 chose;

00:08:12.110 --> 00:08:14.685
Player 2 chose S_2*
and he says, "no that's the best

00:08:14.685 --> 00:08:16.797
I could have done.
Given that Player 2 did in fact

00:08:16.797 --> 00:08:18.636
choose S_2*,
I have no regrets about

00:08:18.636 --> 00:08:21.666
choosing S_1*;
that in fact was my best

00:08:21.666 --> 00:08:24.186
response."
Notice that wouldn't be true at

00:08:24.186 --> 00:08:26.573
the other outcome.
So, for example,

00:08:26.573 --> 00:08:31.156
if Player 1 had chosen
S_1* but Player 2 had

00:08:31.156 --> 00:08:35.840
chosen some other strategy,
let's say S_2 prime,

00:08:35.840 --> 00:08:38.210
then Player I would have
regrets.

00:08:38.210 --> 00:08:40.322
Player I would wake up the next
morning and say,

00:08:40.322 --> 00:08:42.929
"oh I thought Player 1 was
going to play S_2*;

00:08:42.929 --> 00:08:45.600
in fact, she chose
S_2 prime.

00:08:45.600 --> 00:08:47.980
I regret having chosen
S_1*;

00:08:47.980 --> 00:08:51.720
I would have rather chosen
S_1 prime.

00:08:51.720 --> 00:08:54.930
So, only at the Nash
Equilibrium are there no

00:08:54.930 --> 00:08:56.580
regrets.
Everyone okay with that?

00:08:56.580 --> 00:09:00.302
This is just revisiting really
what we did last time and

00:09:00.302 --> 00:09:03.536
underlining these points.
So, I want to spend quite a lot

00:09:03.536 --> 00:09:06.350
of time today just getting used
to the idea of Nash Equilibrium

00:09:06.350 --> 00:09:08.120
and trying to find Nash
Equilibrium.

00:09:08.120 --> 00:09:12.025
(I got to turn off that
projector that's in the way

00:09:12.025 --> 00:09:14.127
there.
Is that going to upset the

00:09:14.127 --> 00:09:17.139
lights a lot?) So okay,
so what I want to do is I want

00:09:17.139 --> 00:09:20.265
to look at some very simple
games with a small number of

00:09:20.265 --> 00:09:22.996
players to start with,
and a small number of

00:09:22.996 --> 00:09:26.473
strategies, and I want us to get
used to how we would find the

00:09:26.473 --> 00:09:28.809
Nash Equilibria in those simple
games.

00:09:28.809 --> 00:09:32.200
We'll start slowly and then
we'll get a little faster.

00:09:32.200 --> 00:09:37.401
So, let's start with this game,
very simple game with two

00:09:37.401 --> 00:09:39.403
players.
Each player has three

00:09:39.403 --> 00:09:42.060
strategies and I'm not going to
motivate this game.

00:09:42.060 --> 00:09:46.304
It's just some random game.
Player 1 can choose up,

00:09:46.304 --> 00:09:50.735
middle, or down,
and Player 2 can choose left,

00:09:50.735 --> 00:09:59.032
center,
and right and the payoffs are

00:09:59.032 --> 00:10:13.658
as follows: (0,4) (4,0) (5,3)
(4,0) (0,4) (5,3) again (3,5)

00:10:13.658 --> 00:10:19.856
(3,5) and (6,6).
So, we could discuss--if we had

00:10:19.856 --> 00:10:22.578
more time, we could actually
play this game--but isn't a very

00:10:22.578 --> 00:10:25.170
exciting game,
so let's leave our playing for

00:10:25.170 --> 00:10:28.083
later, and instead,
let's try and figure out what

00:10:28.083 --> 00:10:31.784
are the Nash Equilibria in this
game and how we're going to go

00:10:31.784 --> 00:10:34.531
about finding it.
The way we're going to go about

00:10:34.531 --> 00:10:36.990
finding them is going to mimic
what we did last time.

00:10:36.990 --> 00:10:39.610
Last time, we had a more
complicated game which was two

00:10:39.610 --> 00:10:41.600
players with a continuum of
strategies,

00:10:41.600 --> 00:10:44.654
and what we did was we figured
out Player 1's best responses

00:10:44.654 --> 00:10:47.606
and Player 2's best responses:
Player 1's best response to

00:10:47.606 --> 00:10:50.919
what Player 2's doing and Player
2's best response to what Player

00:10:50.919 --> 00:10:53.394
1 is doing;
and then we looked where they

00:10:53.394 --> 00:10:55.870
coincided and that was the Nash
Equilibrium.

00:10:55.870 --> 00:10:59.458
We're going to do exactly the
same in this simple game here,

00:10:59.458 --> 00:11:02.986
so we're going to start off by
figuring out what Player 1's

00:11:02.986 --> 00:11:08.230
best response looks like.
