00:49:45.949 --> 00:49:48.392
So, here we have a game with
two equilibria,

00:49:48.392 --> 00:49:49.869
one is good,
one is bad;

00:49:49.869 --> 00:49:53.030
one is really quite bad,
its pareto dominated.

00:49:53.030 --> 00:49:56.378
Notice that what happened here,
the way we spiraled down

00:49:56.378 --> 00:49:59.969
coincides with something we've
talked about Nash Equilibrium

00:49:59.969 --> 00:50:04.155
already,
it coincides with this idea of

00:50:04.155 --> 00:50:09.422
a self-fulfilling prediction.
Provided you think other people

00:50:09.422 --> 00:50:12.519
are not going to invest,
you're not going to invest.

00:50:12.519 --> 00:50:15.576
So, it's a self-fulfilling
prediction to take you down to

00:50:15.576 --> 00:50:17.895
not investing.
Conversely, provided everyone

00:50:17.895 --> 00:50:21.034
thinks everyone else is going to
invest, then you're going to go

00:50:21.034 --> 00:50:23.869
up to the good equilibrium.
I think that corresponds to

00:50:23.869 --> 00:50:26.648
what the gentleman said in the
middle about a bare market

00:50:26.648 --> 00:50:28.730
versus a bull market.
If it was a bare market,

00:50:28.730 --> 00:50:30.697
it looked like everyone else
didn't have confidence in

00:50:30.697 --> 00:50:33.787
everyone else investing,
and then that was a

00:50:33.787 --> 00:50:40.489
self-fulfilling prophesy and we
ended up with no investment.

00:50:40.489 --> 00:50:43.730
Now, we've seen bad outcomes in
the class before.

00:50:43.730 --> 00:50:46.317
For example,
the very first day we saw a

00:50:46.317 --> 00:50:49.511
